abstract = "This article is a revision of the previous edition article by F. Hay, volume 1, pp. 62–73, © 2003, Elsevier Ltd. Abstract Seed banks are facilities dedicated to the medium-term storage (for a few decades; storage at 5–10 °C) or long-term storage (for many decades; storage at −18 ± 3 °C) of samples of seeds (‘accessions’) as a means of conserving crop or species diversity. A seed bank conserving crop varieties is often called a genebank as the seed samples (accessions) are used as a source of genes conferring desirable characteristics. Conventional seed banking involves drying orthodox seeds to low moisture content prior to storage. Seeds are also cleaned, tested for germination and health, and then sealed in (ideally) airtight, moisture-proof containers. Seed banks actively manage their collection(s), testing seeds for viability (germination) at regular intervals and, if necessary, recollecting or rejuvenating samples. Most seed banks also actively distribute seeds for use by plant breeders and other researchers, as permitted by relevant legislation. Seed bank databases store all the passport and seed management data. "
