abstract = "Millions of hectares of land on lower slopes of inland valleys in the rolling peneplain of humid and sub humid West Africa are considered to be more suitable for rice production than their upland counterparts. Suitable varieties, however, are still needed to fully exploit the potentials of these lands. Two field experiments were carried out in 1983 and 1984 to evaluate the performance of different rice genotypes planted to a slope of an inland valley in western Nigeria. The experimental slope was divided into four zones based on the depth of ground water-table and its fluctuation. Drought stress, blast and grain discoloration are major constraints to rice in Zone I where the ground water-table nerver rises to above 60 cm below soil surface, and upland genotypes are invariably outyielded by lowland ones. In Zones \{III\} and \{IV\} where ground water never drops below 40 cm below surface, rice never showed drought-stress symptoms and lowland genotypes outyielded upland ones. In Zone II, where ground watertable fluctuated between 20 and 80 cm below surface, no clear difference in performance could be drawn between the two genotypical groups. Yields of rice ranged from 0 to 200, 20 to 250, 190 to 600, and 110 to 400 g/m2, respectively, in Zones I, II, III, and IV. "
}
