abstract = "The Sequiviridae is a relatively newly recognized family of viruses. Viruses belonging to the family Sequiviridae infect plants and are transmitted by insects in a semipersistent manner. The family Sequiviridae is divided into two genera: Sequivirus and Waikavirus. Parsnip yellow fleck virus (PYFV) is the type member of sequiviruses, while rice tungro spherical virus (RTSV), maize chlorotic dwarf virus (MCDV), and anthriscus yellows virus are classified as the members of waikaviruses. Most viruses belonging to the family Sequiviridae function as or require a helper virus in insect transmission. The viruses have isometric particles encapsidating a monopartite, positive-sense, single-stranded \{RNA\} genome. The length of genome varies, ranging from approximately 10 kb for sequiviruses to 12 kb for waikaviruses. The genomes are similar in structure to those of picornaviruses, and encode a large polyprotein. The polyprotein is proteolytically cleaved into three capsid proteins: a cysteine proteinase, an RNA-dependent \{RNA\} polymerase, and putative proteins of unknown functions. Nonstructural proteins of the viruses belonging to Sequiviridae show extensive sequence similarities to those of comoviruses and picornaviruses. Isolates showing distinctive biological characteristics were found within each of PYFV, RTSV, and MCDV. Sequence analyses revealed that a significant genetic variation exists among the isolates of different viruses. "
}
