abstract = "Publisher Summary This chapter focuses on nitrogen transformation processes in wetland rice soils. It summarizes information on the physical, physicochemical, and biochemical processes relevant to nitrogen transformations and to improving fertilizer nitrogen efficiency in wetland soils. Wetland soils differ markedly from well-drained dryland soils. The characteristics of the wetland rice soils have been studied and reported. Some dynamic aspects of the wetland rice soils that are pertinent to nitrogen transformations are summarized as retardation of gaseous exchange between flooded soil and atmosphere. In the wetland rice soil, a reduced plow layer is sandwiched between a thin oxidized surface soil layer and a partly oxidized subsurface soil layer. Within the reduced soil layer, in which most of rice roots proliferate and derive nitrogen, is a complex mosaic consisting of aerobic and anaerobic microsystems. Flooding soil results in the accumulation of ammonium, the instability of nitrate, and a lowered nitrogen requirement for organic matter decomposition. Flooding also causes inefficient utilization of applied nitrogen. Ammoniacal nitrogen is subject to fixation by clays, loss by volatilization, leaching, runoff, seepage, and nitrification followed by loss through denitrification. "
}
