abstract = "An inter-laboratory collaborative test on the measurement of grain elongation of milled rice during cooking was undertaken in 1982 on five selected milled rice samples with the use of a simple common method in 19 laboratories in 16 countries. The common method involved soaking rice grains for 30 min and then direct transfer of the soaked grains to a boiling water bath for 10 min. Elongation ratio (ratio of mean length of cooked and raw grains) and elongation index (ratio of mean length-to- width ratios of cooked and raw grains) showed similar rankings of the samples, but statistical analysis showed interaction between sample, collaborator and method. Variation due to sample was generally higher in the common method than in the conventional methods used in different laboratories. Elongation ratio measurement provides more consistent results than elongation index and is simpler, requiring the measurement of grain length only. "
