keywords = "Carbon dioxide",
keywords = "Oryza sativa ",
abstract = "Atmospheric \{CO2\} is expected to exceed 600 μl 1−1 by the 21st century and is predicted to increase global mean temperature by 0–8°C. Because \{CO2\} and temperature are expected to increase together, we conducted controlled-environment chamber research to assess the effects of two \{CO2\} concentrations (330 and 660 μl 1−1) and three temperature regimes (29/21, 33/25, 37/29°C, day/night temperature) on three lowland (IR28, IR36, IR64) and three upland (ITA186, Moroberekan, Salumpikit) rice cultivars. At 330 μl l−1 CO2, most cultivars grew best at 33/25°C. Doubling \{CO2\} increased plant height by 17% at 29/21°C and by 7% at 33/25°C, but reduced plant height by 3% at 37/29°C. Increasing temperature from 29/21 to 37/29°C reduced tiller number by 10% but doubling \{CO2\} more than offset this effect so that tiller number was 66% greater in the high CO2, high temperature treatment than in the low CO2, low temperature treatment at 45 days after sowing. In the lowland cultivars the combination of higher \{CO2\} and higher temperaure doubly shortened the vegetative and reproductive phase, while at 29/21°C, increased \{CO2\} delayed onset of the reproductive phase. At 29/21°C, doubling \{CO2\} increased time to flowering by 6% but at 37/29°C, doubling \{CO2\} decreased time to flowering by 6%. Flowering of \{ITA\} 186 was not affected by \{CO2\} level. Doubling \{CO2\} increased total dry weight at flowering by 22%. Total dry weight was inversely related to high temperature for the lowland cultivars. Although controlled-environment experiments have their drawbacks, the present data indicate varietal differences in responses to \{CO2\} and temperature and a significant interactive effects of \{CO2\} and temperature on development of lowland rices. These differences may provide options to minimise adverse effects of future climate changes. "
}
@article{Garrity199583,
