abstract = "Abstract The introduction of fertilizer-responsive early-maturing semi-dwarf varieties and other aspects of modern rice technology in tropical Asia make early and timely weed control highly critical if high yields are to be obtained. In transplanted rice, hand weeding is the most common weed control method in South and Southeast Asia. Phenoxy acid herbicides such as 2,4-D and \{MCPA\} and some selective herbicides such as butachlor and thiobencarb are used by a few rice farmers. As labor costs rise, chemical methods of weed control combined with cultural practices and other direct methods provide attractive alternatives to hand weeding. Furthermore, with area under wet seeding increasing in some places, chemical weed control will play a more important role. Countries with high cost of labor and good control over irrigation water such as Japan, Korea, and Taiwan, use herbicides on 75 to 100% of their rice. "
