keywords = "New-plant-type rice variety",
keywords = "Pleiotropic effect ",
abstract = "Abstract To enhance the yield potential of an elite indica rice cultivar, an introgression (BC3-derived) line of IR64, YTH288, was developed using a new-plant-type cultivar, IR66215-44-2-3, as a donor parent. \{YTH288\} has agronomically valuable characteristics such as large panicles, few unproductive tillers, and large leaves inherited from NPT. To identify the genetic basis of these traits, we used 167 \{F2\} plants derived from a cross between \{IR64\} and \{YTH288\} to conduct \{QTL\} analysis for five agronomic traits: days to heading (DTH), culm length (CL), flag leaf length (FLL), flag leaf width (FLW), and filled spikelet number per panicle (FSN). Six putative \{QTL\} were detected: four on chromosome 4 (for CL, FLL, FLW, and FSN) and two on chromosome 2 (for \{DTH\} and FLL). All \{QTL\} with the IR66215-44-2-3 allele, except that for \{FLL\} on chromosome 2, had positive effects on each trait. To confirm the effects of these putative QTL, we developed \{NILs\} with the \{IR64\} genetic background by marker-assisted selection. We observed significant differences in several agronomic traits between \{IR64\} and \{NILs\} that carried these \{QTL\} on chromosomes 2 and 4. Additionally, four IR64-NILs carrying chromosomal segments derived from different \{NPT\} varieties on the long arm of chromosome 4 exhibited similar pleiotropic effects for unique agronomic traits. These \{NILs\} can be used as research materials for studying each trait and as breeding materials for yield improvement of indica rice cultivars. "
}
