author = "Bruce R. Thomas and John Chandler and Raymond L. Rodriguez and Carl R. Simmons and Ning Huang and Erik Karrer",
abstract = "Abstract Plant cell fermentation based on cereal species like rice may be a useful system for the industrial-scale production of plant α-amylases and other recombinant proteins. In the example described below, two genes in the rice α-amylase gene family (RAmy3D and RAmy3E) produce 20% to 40% of the total protein secreted in rice cell suspension cultures. The salient features of the rice cell fermentation system include high-level, regulated expression and secretion of α-amylase proteins into the culture medium. Furthermore, the lower temperatures required for plant cell culture and a simple medium based on sucrose instead of glucose may provide the cost advantage needed to make plant cell fermentation of proteins competitive with microbial fermentation systems. Cell culture also provides a model system to study the biochemistry, genetics and molecular biology of genes expressed in cell culture. Transgenic rice cell lines have been used to demonstrate the metabolic regulation of one of the rice α-amylase genes, RAmy3D. The transcription of \{RAmy3D\} in cell culture is induced 165-fold when sucrose is removed from the culture medium. Similar regulation of \{RAmy3D\} has been observed in the rice plant. The RAmy3D/GUS promoter–reporter gene fusion is just one of many gene constructs that can be used to investigate the transcriptional, translational and post-translational characteristics of this system. Such information is crucial for the development of efficient and economical protein expression systems based on plant cell fermentation. "
}
